text: 2/Putin launched a full-scale invasion of #Ukraine in February with an insufficient force that's since been exhausted in pursuit of limited gains, an error in campaign design from which Russia has yet to recover.

text: 3/Efforts to replenish Russia's troop shortage short of mobilization have failed. A call for a partial mobilization is thus Putin‚Äôs attempt to reconcile the gap between his unchanged intent ‚Äì which is to control all of Ukraine - and Russia's rapidly degrading capability to do so.

text: 5/Many Russians support the war rhetorically but are not willing to fight in it. #Russia will also face limitations in throughput and deployment of these forces ‚Äì both efforts require officer cadre ‚Äì an increasingly diminishing resource and bottleneck in the Russian military.
context_annotations: [{"domain": {"id": "123", "name": "Ongoing News Story", "description": "Ongoing News Stories like 'Brexit'"}, "entity": {"id": "1484601166080081920", "name": "Russo-Ukrainian conflict"}}]

text: 6/Equipping these forces will be another challenge, and the shortcomings of #Russia's defense industrial base will only compound this problem. It is essential for that reason that the West keeps and expands its export controls on electronics.

text: 7/ We should not be overly dismissive of the mobilization either. We should watch how Russia will integrate this force, how it will train it, and the resulting effect it will produce on the battlefield, which we are unlikely to see until 2023.

text: 8/#Putin's value proposition to his base for many years has been a promise of a "great Russia." This value proposition is being challenged now, in part because of Russian setbacks in ##Ukraine. He is not imminently vulnerable, but he's more vulnerable than he has been in years.

text: 9/#Putin is trying to reconcile irreconcilable realities - keeping up this promise of the "great Russia," his eroding capability to deliver on it, as well as the unwillingness of the Russian people to fight in this war.

text: 10/While we cannot rule out Putin's use of a tactical nuclear weapon in Ukraine, there are two critical points worth stating. First, Ukraine has been taking on that risk since the day it chose to push back on Russia‚Äôs full-scale invasion.

text: 11/It's Ukraine's and Ukraine's decision only whether to continue running that risk. So far Ukraine has chosen to run that risk ‚Äì in part because the alternative, for many, is worse. It's Bucha. It's Izyum.

text: 12/Additionally, such a strike is unlikely to break Ukraine's will to fight, which is one of the two key centers of gravity of this war ‚Äì along with Western support.

Russia requested the call, according to The New York Times. Per the White House, Putin and Biden spoke for about 50 minutes. The leaders last call that was made known to the public was on December 7, when Russia said it would send ideas on the crisis to Washington "within a week," Reuters reported. The US Air Force flew two reconnaissance missions over eastern Ukraine this week, the first on December 27 just a few days after Russia said it would withdraw 10,000 troops from the shared border, CNN reported.

More on the leaders’ call:
- Ukraine has been a point of contention for the two countries since the annexation of Crimea in 2014, Al Jazeera reports

- Russia denied a new assault on Ukraine during the previous conversation and warned against any NATO military involvement, according to Reuters and Al Jazeera

Vladimir Putin and US President Joe Biden spoke again on the phone Thursday afternoon about Ukraine. Russia requested the call, according to The New York Times. Per the White House, Putin and Biden spoke for about 50 minutes. The leaders last call that was made known to the public was on December 7, when Russia said it would send ideas on the crisis to Washington "within a week," Reuters reported. The US Air Force flew two reconnaissance missions over eastern Ukraine this week, the first on December 27 just a few days after Russia said it would withdraw 10,000 troops from the shared border, CNN reported.

More on the leaders’ call:
